Foaming <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/udefila.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Defila</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/16/02 10:19:09 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthetavern.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=907.topic&index=248>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.steelwarrior.org/forum/p_die.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: doh</span><hr size=1> Well, I'll tell you what, you can tank again when I get back:<br>
<br>
-Invisibility (Cobalt Greaves, Larrikan's Mask, Incarndine BP)<br>
-Lifetaps (countless weapons)<br>
-Snare (silken whip)<br>
-DOTs (Bloodfire, Rotwood Club, etc etc etc)<br>
-Heals (Cobalt BP, all Velious BP's)<br>
-Stuns<br>
-Damage Shields<br>
<br>
as the exclusive domain of the hybrid classes.<br>
<br>
And other procs and effects that are available in the 50+ game. I started a Shadow Knight because I wanted these spells and abilities, yet I came to the realization at level 50 that with enough pp and the right friends/guild, any warrrior could duplicate the arsenal that I had sacrificed my melee/tanking abilities for. This erosion of class boundaries began with Kunark, and has continued to this day.<br>
<br>
Much the same as the all/all melee class gear from places such as NToV, Ssra and other high-end dungeons blur the abilities of Warriors from other pure melee classes. The difference is for non-warriors, it either takes hard work (getting to these dungeons) or sheer mudflation (ever taken a twink to Sol A with velious-era gear? can you say &quot;self-powerlevelling?&quot;) to trivialize the content. EQ's designers are at fault for this erosion of class lines, and no one seems to complain when it suits them. In fact, it was pule melees clamoring for &quot;magic&quot; that resulted in the creation of Kunark Armors, which started this mess in my opinion. So here we are, all playing a game, where everyone got what they wanted, and still no one is content.<br>
<br>
My SK sits at 1400ac and 5400hp raid-buffed (nothing uber, but respectable), and no one tells me to stop tanking till we reach a mob that flurries. And then, I step back and let the Warrior do his job, because he's got the hp to handle it, and besides, I make a much better offtank/caster tank for hairy situations. Why should I try and push that envelope when there's a better tool for the job? I have 30aa points, some OK gear, and I worked my butt off to make this first toon as good as I could. But I wouldn't say the gear I have is used by every SK you run across, it's above average, and as a result, so is my ability to tank. If the people who have worked as hard as I have for their equipment are the problem, then y'all are a being a bit hypersensitive, methinks.<br>
<br>
This game was more fun when there was a sense of interdependence, but when you can have a full group chain-pulling in mindless EXP mills like Fungus Grove/Velk's without even the thought of a healer crossing your mind, who isn't going to take the path of least resistance?<br>
<br>
Everyone's always asking for something, my question to the Warrior community is, what are you willing to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> give up</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for it? The damage is apparantly already done, so now what?<br>
