<br>
My choice for a main tank as a cleric is a very simple one: who am I going to have to heal the least in a session?  Yes, a good paladin or shadowknight can tank very well, and I know of a few rangers who are so ridiculously decked out that they can tank better than some paladins and shadowknights.  But sorry hybrids, give me a well equipped warrior and I'll tell you where you can stick your taunt button.<br>
<br>
No one takes a beating the way a warrior does.  Granted, if not properly equipped they get chewed through as easily as the hybrid &quot;tanks,&quot; but I'm going on the assumption that being a 58th cleric means I'm not going to be healing any clowns wearing full crusty.  Most of the nods I see being given to Frodlin's post are in the area of taunting.  But from the perspective of sitting on my pasty high elf duff and watching fight after fight after fight, let me offer another facet of the taunt problem.<br>
<br>
Warriors' taunt defficiency is based on two factors.  A) The warrior needs a stronger taunt - I agree with this, even based only on my level 35 warrior (who struggles to keep taunt off of rangers wielding Wurmslayers who think they're supposed to be taunting off of me /sigh).  B) The &quot;damage support&quot; classes - rogues and monks, and to a lesser extent paladins and shadowknights - aren't using their &quot;aggro controls&quot; or &quot;taunts&quot; correctly.<br>
<br>
So to review point B:<br>
<br>
Very few things piss me off as a cleric more than being in a group where I'm healing 2 or 3 melees every fight.  The ideal situation is for the mob to be pulled, tank establishes and holds aggro, and the mob is systematically torn to shreds.  However, what I normally see in non-guild groups is that the mob is pulled, everyone starts beating on it, and the mob bounces from the tank to the rogue to the monk to the rogue to the chanter to the monk, etc etc ad naseum.<br>
<br>
MONKS have a f'n FEIGN DEATH button for a reason.  It is not there just to split up spawns or so they can take a nap and leave their character laying around.  I also play a 43rd monk.  When she gains aggro, I turn off auto-attack, feign death, and then stand and continue attacking.  This was not rocket science; if the cleric is healing two people, mana burns twice as fast, pulls and exp come twice as slow.  Simple logic, really.<br>
<br>
ROGUES have a skill called EVADE.  I do not blame rogues who generate too much aggro 100%.  A lot of the problem is that Evade doesn't work most of the time.  Probably the most ingenious thing I have ever seen a rogue do was create a macro that had the commands to 1) backstab 2) turn off auto-attack 3) Hide 4) pause 5) Auto-attack.<br>
<br>
PALADINS, SHADOWKNIGHTS, and RANGERS (and even secondary/tertiary warriors) - if you are not the main tank and you are taunting, YOU ARE AN IDIOT.<br>
<br>
PALADINS usually have a tendency to generate too much aggro from over-stunning.  I don't see this happen as much now in the higher end exp groupings, but it does still happen from time to time.  Basic premise when there is a warrior in the group - &quot;If you have aggro, you're screwing something up.&quot; [except in the odd case where the paladin has a higher ac and hps than the warrior (God forbid)].<br>
<br>
SHADOWKNIGHTS tend to generate wicked aggro because they DoT and Lifetap the @#%$ out of anything that steps in front of them.  Darkness snares are nice but generally can wait until later in the fight, after the tank has generated sufficient aggro through Taunting, and so it doesn't wear off before the mob actually starts to run.<br>
<br>
RANGERS can deal out a ludicrous amount of damage given the right weapons, and their epics tend to generate a lot of aggro when they proc the DoT/Slow.  I don't know much about the &quot;Jolt&quot; spells but they reduce aggro from what I have heard.  My only real recommendation for rangers is attack from the rear-flank (yes, even if there is a rogue).  Reduced riposte damage = less healing the cleric has to do, and more damage that character can dish out without interruption.<br>
<br>
The biggest misconception amongst many players, in my opinion, is that all melees except the rogue should be attacking from the front.  I don't agree; if the proper steps are being followed to let the main tank hold aggro (see the above complaints), then he/she should be the only person in front of the mob.  Keeping everyone else out of the block/parry/dodge/riposte arc of the mob is increasing the DPS of the group and decreasing the DPS of the mob.  If this is followed, and the mob is slowed, its DPS basically drops to absolute squat (relatively speaking) and you'll find your exp goes a LOT faster.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<br>
Okay, now that that crap is out of the way, we can complain about other stuff.<br>
<br>
&quot;Combat Fury&quot;<br>
<br>
I agree, Paladins and (to a lesser extent in my opinion) Shadowknights have been and probably still are in many cases highly underrated and underappreciated classes.  This is not the fault of the warrior, and the warrior should not be penalized in an attempt to make these valuable hybrid classes better appreciated by the average pickup group.<br>
<br>
A warrior is not just a fighter; you do not stick a longsword in the hand of a peasant and call them a warrior.  A warrior is someone who has undergone some type of training (most likely military) and who is skilled with the upkeep of his weapons and his equipment (armor).  A warrior is trained in how best to harm his enemies - to strike for the CRITICAL areas and to CRIPPLE them.  Hence the Critical Hits and Crippling Blows.<br>
<br>
Now, if you give this skill to all melees, you've basically stripped the warrior of a unique facet of his existence.  You can shrug these attacks off as &quot;eye candy,&quot; but do try to keep in mind that beyond all the numbers and names and statistics, Everquest is a roleplaying game too.  You don't have much to celebrate as a warrior if you say &quot;I slashed a dragon's hamstring for 600 points of damage&quot; if the paladin turns around and says &quot;Well I gouged out his eye for 1200 damage and then healed myself up while you were binding your wounds&quot; or the shadowknight says &quot;I just slashed his balls off for 1000 damage and Harm Touched his sorry ass for another 1000, and Feigned Death so I didn't get hurt at all.&quot;<br>
<br>
Criticals for other melees, from a more logic-oriented standpoint, also means they are generating more aggro.  What the hell inspired VI to want that, guess for yourselves.<br>
<br>
&quot;Warrior AA Skills&quot;<br>
<br>
My warrior is only level 35, but I of course checked her AA Skill Tree as soon as it came about.  Frodlin could better fill you in on all the individual deficiencies of the skills, but I'll just say that warriors are sorely lacking in my opinion.  Just compare to what other classes are getting, and it becomes easily apparent.  Paladins got Slay Undead, which makes them the bane of anything undead (with 5000pt slays like Frodlin mentioned), but they *also* get Critical Hits like a warrior too.  They get a free horse.  They get the ability to use LoH as a Complete heal.  Etc...<br>
<br>
How about:<br>
<br>
&gt; Give the warrior an increased taunt - most mobs have a mother, let's see some really interesting taunt messages.  <br>
<br>
&gt; Give the warrior the ability to stun/interrupt casts with his kick - hell, they gave the pallies/SKs the ability to bash with a 2HS (don't even have to use AA if they're epic'ed), while warriors lose the bash skill when they get dual wield*.<br>
<br>
&gt; Fix Flurry - if it works for the mobs, it sure as @#%$ should work for the PCs; otherwise, break it for the mobs too.<br>
<br>
&gt; Put a fixed duration on a berserker frenzy - you get beat up for all that time and then it's over as soon as the cleric heals you?  Hell no, your warrior gets pissed off he should stay that way til he's had time to cool off.<br>
<br>
&gt; As I mentioned earlier, a warrior is generally a tactician and has limited to extensive knowledge of his enemies.  How about a skill button called &quot;Expose Weakness&quot; that warriors could obtain in the mid 40s or something, that lowers the mob's AC?  Give them a skill in between Disarm (oh how useful) and the disciplines that really sets them apart from the other fighters, and it would also be a HUGE aggro bonus to the warrior.<br>
<br>
* - Granted, giving this ability would diminish the usefulness/uniqueness of the large races' Slam ability, but I think it is something the warrior needs.<br>
<br>
*****<br>
<br>
In summary, I agree with Frodlin that the warrior class needs some work.  Not asking for anything ridiculous that is going to make them blow away every other melee class, just some hefty improvements to what they already possess that will more accurately distinguish them from their other melee allies.  The warrior counts on everyone else to perform their function to the max of their ability - now we need VI to help the warrior do so himself.<br>
<br>
--------------------<br>
Audrei Talvorus<br>
58th Templar of the Lord<br>
Forged Souls<br>
The Seventh Hammer<br>
<br>
Karian Vanador<br>
35th Warrior<br>
Forged Souls<br>
