<br>
Having read through this thread and many of the sub-threads that have resulted from it, I think I've adjusted my thoughts to streamline things, and to keep in mind the balance of the game and the challenges it presents, preserving and balancing the difficulties of the high end game with the struggles at the low-mid-up to high end game.<br>
<br>
Taunt:  I still think that it needs a MAJOR review/retune.  In order not to completely trivialize the high end game, it wouldn't be wise to make taunt totaly reliable against super high end mobs.  <br>
<br>
The balance comes in in that the false distinction between a 59 warrior and a 60 warrior should probably vanish.   A warrior should have a chance to taunt, period, just as a rogue has a chance to backstab.   Just because an arbitrary level has been placed on a mob shouldn't disable a warrior's ability to see some action, albeit at a reduced rate from one of his buttons.  A warrior is the *only* class in game that cannot use a certain skill that they've had from the beginning against a specific type of mob.   Taunt should work, perhaps less reliably, but should actually do something against mobs which are yellow and red regardless of level.<br>
<br>
Taunt should probably remain the same as it works currently against yellow/red con mobs so as to make encounters have some semblance of a challenge.<br>
<br>
Now, for mobs that are less powerful in theory than the warrior (blue cons and lower) taunt should be given a serious upgrade.  This would allow warriors during experience sessions to be a viable tank.   With the advent of free exp zones such as Velk's, Fungus Grove, Akheva, The Grey, etc.. It makes no sense to impose a &quot;challenge restriction&quot; on one class but not others.   Let's face it, since the advent of AAXP, exp camping isn't challenging, it's merely the necessary timesink to gain your skills, and the further the gains, the more trivial the challenge, except in some great zones like Cazic Thule.   To enable a greater abiliy to taunt mobs that con blue or lower doesn't jeapordize gameplay one iota, but merely makes warriors able to do the job which has been designed for them.<br>
<br>
Defense Skills:<br>
<br>
/disc defensive is a crutch, and and excuse to beat down warrios ever since we got it.  I think the &quot;Putting the warriors on their own defensive table&quot; idea is the most reasonable.   I don't want to be overpowered, but I want to be the most logical choice as a tank.  There was this nice balance with Hybrids before, sure they could generate more aggro, but didn't WANT to, they would get hurt.  If there was a warrior and a knight in the group, you'd WANT the warrior to be taking the damage.  I think this was a good balance.   You should want a warrior to be the tank of choice no matter what, because they exchanged utility for it.   It shouldn't be like before where no warrior=no group, but there NEEDS to be a line of demarcation where the warrior should be the #1 tank in the game, period.  This would mean that it'd need to be costly enough to see the benefit of having a warrior in the group, with Paladins/SK's able to fill in if need be.  It used to be, pre-cap that armor would make the difference, but with the AC softcap, it makes no difference any more.  Therefore, there should be a table which gives back that line.<br>
<br>
